result.execSummary:
The defendant Anthony David Hales Sr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Anthony David Hales Sr is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Anthony David Hales Sr was found guilty of OWI (4th w/ Passenger < 16 Yrs Old), an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).
  • Anthony David Hales Sr was found guilty of Neglecting a Child, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 948.21(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Anthony David Hales in court with attorney Matthew Russell Meyer.  Defendant Anthony David Hales in custody.  Ron Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk  As to Counts 1 & 3: Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum and Jury Instructions received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
As to Count 2:  As a matter of law count is dismissed.
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  Court ordered the defendant provide a DNA sample.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant. 
As to Count 1:  The Court sentenced the defendant to serve 1 YEAR straight time at the House of Corrections with 64 days credi
As to Count 3:  6 months in the House of Correction,  CONSECUTIVE  to Count 1.
These sentences are consecutive to any other sentence.
Court stayed the sentence on Count 3 and placed the defendant on 1 year probation.
  Conditions of Probation:
- No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
- Cooperate with the Probation Department
- No possession of weapons
- no voting until his civil rights are restored
- 30 hours of community service
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- Absolute/maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs.
- No possession/consumption/selling/distribution of illegal drugs/alcohol.  No possession of drug paraphrenalia
- Random urine screens.
- Obtain/maintain fulltime employment/education/vocation.
- Provide a DNA sample.

Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
Fine in the amount of $1200.00; 
Pay the blood draw fee of $17.50 to the West Allis Police Department on Count 1; 
Court assessed court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA surcharge) on Count 1 only; 
Court waived court costs on Count 3 due to the fine assessed.
-  No Cash Bail Posted in this matter  
Court ordered Intoxicated Driver Assessment; form filed; copy to defendant.
Court ordered defendant's operating privileges revoked for 4 years with the mandatory reinstatement fee.  
Defendant's operating privilege for operation of Class D vehicles is restricted to operating vehicles that are equipped with an ignition interlock device; and each motor vehicle for which the defendant's name appears on the vehicle's certificate of title or registration must be equipped with an ignition interlock device beginning on the date the department issues any license and for a period of 3 years thereafter.
